<subSubSection id="5FF065107D13FFEA65ADF88DFC7FADD6" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="14" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="1755369B7D13FFEA65ADF88DFC7FADD6" blockId="12.[150,1437,1582,1930]" lastBlockId="13.[151,1436,151,391]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="14" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="259EEA897D13FFEB65ADF88DFE7FAB36" bold="true" box="[199,398,1870,1895]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="259EEA897D13FFEB65ADF88DFEB0AB36" box="[199,321,1870,1895]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" reason="1">
<emphasis id="259EEA897D13FFEB65ADF88DFECBAB36" bold="true" box="[199,314,1870,1895]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Male:
</emphasis>
Color similar to 
<taxonomicName id="D0EA4D187D13FFEB673AF88CFD2FAB37" authorityName="Costa &amp; Santos" authorityYear="2000" box="[592,734,1871,1894]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="muryense">
<emphasis id="259EEA897D13FFEB673AF88CFD2FAB37" box="[592,734,1871,1894]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">H. muryense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figs. 36A–B, 37A–B) but lacking sub-basal spine. Cercus in lateral view: small dorsobasal expansion present. Ventrobasal expansion occupying more than 1/2 length. Curved downward (Fig. 24B). cercus in mediodorsal view: Apical portion shorter, basal and medial portions subequal. Ventral expansion present and sparsely hairy on ventral border. Ventral branch of medial process wide plate, quite triangular but with curved step on external side; high sclerotized ridge reaching external side at base of curved step and reaching also base of dorsal branch. Dorsal branch of medial process very small, triangular, with two sides smaller than base, internal side sparsely toothed (Fig. 24A). 
<emphasis id="259EEA897D12FFEA6628FF23FC68ACA9" bold="true" box="[834,921,224,248]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Female</emphasis>
: Posterior lobe of prothorax very narrow and roughly semicircular with small notch in middle, pale brown with large ovoid black spot in middle. Tips covered with short hairs (Fig.45D); Valves of ovipositor surpassing distal S10 and ventral margin with small spines (
<figureCitation id="8FD12A1E7D12FFEA6005FEE4FF38AD35" captionStart="FIGURE 48" captionStartId="59.[151,250,1473,1496]" captionTargetBox="[405,1165,197,1445]" captionTargetId="figure-45@59.[392,1194,193,1453]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="FIGURE 48. Female: Heteragrion muryense (A) S8–S10, (B) basal plate; Heteragrion tiradentense (allotype) (C) S8–S10, (D) basal plate; Heteragrion flavovittatum (E) S8–S10, (F) basal plate; Heteragrion ictericum (G) S8–S10, (H) basal plate." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 48C</figureCitation>
); Cercus longer than S10, without bristles at tip (
<figureCitation id="8FD12A1E7D12FFEA679CFE8FFCAFAD35" box="[758,862,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURE 48" captionStartId="59.[151,250,1473,1496]" captionTargetBox="[405,1165,197,1445]" captionTargetId="figure-45@59.[392,1194,193,1453]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="FIGURE 48. Female: Heteragrion muryense (A) S8–S10, (B) basal plate; Heteragrion tiradentense (allotype) (C) S8–S10, (D) basal plate; Heteragrion flavovittatum (E) S8–S10, (F) basal plate; Heteragrion ictericum (G) S8–S10, (H) basal plate." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 48C</figureCitation>
); Basal plate: dorsal edge concave, longer than the convex outer edge. Ventral side 1/3 length of outer edge (
<figureCitation id="8FD12A1E7D12FFEA6672FEACFC73ADD6" box="[792,898,367,391]" captionStart="FIGURE 48" captionStartId="59.[151,250,1473,1496]" captionTargetBox="[405,1165,197,1445]" captionTargetId="figure-45@59.[392,1194,193,1453]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="FIGURE 48. Female: Heteragrion muryense (A) S8–S10, (B) basal plate; Heteragrion tiradentense (allotype) (C) S8–S10, (D) basal plate; Heteragrion flavovittatum (E) S8–S10, (F) basal plate; Heteragrion ictericum (G) S8–S10, (H) basal plate." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 48D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
